{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1201"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1201"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.06,0.12,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1201"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31716"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"2411"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44507"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a six-month history of an abdominal swelling. He notices it most when he strains or coughs. The swelling is not painful and he has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history, including no surgical history and takes no regular medications. On examination he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits and his BMI is 30kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Abdominal examination shows that his abdomen is distended and soft. The patient is asked to lift his head and shoulders off the bed (Images 1 - 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weight reduction and exercise","Abdominal binder","Laparoscopic mesh repair","Laparoscopic plication of the recti","Pre-peritoneal mesh repair"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of divarication of the recti - which has come about through a combination of excessive abdominal fat and lack of exercise. These are both factors that have lead to a weakening of the rectus abdominus muscles, with subsequent weakness and protrusion of the abdominal contents through a flaccid and stretched linea alba.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with such a pattern of weakness in their linea alba are frequently referred for a repair of their \u0022incisional hernia\u0022. Such a diagnosis is wrong on two counts. First, there is no incision through which a hernia has developed and second, the problem is not a hernia. A hernia is a protrusion of part of the abdominal cavity through a defect in a part of the abdominal wall. What this patient has is protrusion of abdominal contents against - but not through - the abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment is aimed at getting the patient to \u003Cstrong\u003Elose weight and to strengthen the rectus abdominal muscles through exercise\u003C/strong\u003E. The weakened recti have become pushed to either side. The patient may eventually require some form of surgical approach (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eplication\u003C/strong\u003E), but this should be preceded by physiotherapy, abdominal wall exercises and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal binder\u003C/strong\u003E could be used for patients who have large incisional hernias and who are not considered suitable for surgery to repair the defect. If this patient\u0027s problem was that of an anterior abdominal wall hernia, then some sort of surgical repair could be considered. Small hernias might be suitable for a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic mesh repair\u003C/strong\u003E. Larger hernia would need some sort of open \u003Cstrong\u003Emesh repair\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first-line treatment for rectal divarication is weight loss and exercise."],"references":["Carlstedt A, Bringman S, Egberth M, Emanuelsson P, Olsson A, Petersson U, et al. Management of diastasis of the rectus abdominis muscles: recommendations for swedish national guidelines. Scand J Surg. 2021;110(3):452-459. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8551433/","Jessen ML, \u00d6berg S, Rosenberg J. Treatment Options for Abdominal Rectus Diastasis. Front Surg. 2019;6:65. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6877697/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31716"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1201"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14562"},{"type":"media","id":"14563"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14562"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5257a892-44f8-4b29-9dfe-22d21e54eaba.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5257a892-44f8-4b29-9dfe-22d21e54eaba.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"14563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14563"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0b1c47f7-447b-40f6-9278-1c6b4d2